00:13:15,529 --> 00:13:16,029
can walk around.

246
00:13:16,049 --> 00:13:16,830
You don't have to stand still.

247
00:13:16,890 --> 00:13:18,251
It's not going to disappear if you move around.

248
00:13:20,155 --> 00:13:22,999
A big part of why that happens though is the limited field of view.

249
00:13:23,299 --> 00:13:27,344
Something that the HoloLens has been criticized for and I know upcoming AR headsets kind of

250
00:13:27,364 --> 00:13:28,265
have the same limitation.

251
00:13:29,267 --> 00:13:32,611
The videos that are recorded have holograms present throughout the entire frame.

252
00:13:33,031 --> 00:13:37,016
In reality there's kind of a clipping window that's quite small and it makes it easy, especially

253
00:13:37,036 --> 00:13:38,778
in the helicopter game, to lose track of things.

254
00:13:40,429 --> 00:13:45,674
I use guidance arrows to point out where people should be looking, but I found that the simple

255
00:13:45,774 --> 00:13:49,118
guidance arrow that most people are familiar with if they're gamers, which uses the shortest

256
00:13:49,218 --> 00:13:50,999
angle distance, is very confusing.

257
00:13:51,019 --> 00:13:53,962
What happens is people look down sometimes if there's something behind them, and then

258
00:13:53,982 --> 00:13:57,205
they don't see that thing there, and they're like, well I don't know what's going on, and

259
00:13:57,225 --> 00:13:59,768
they totally ignore the guidance arrows and they get confused.

260
00:14:01,164 --> 00:14:05,649
What I found works much more effectively is just simply limiting it to horizontal movement.

261
00:14:06,029 --> 00:14:11,615
And then once something's within like a range of an angle sweep, then do an up and down guidance.

262
00:14:11,695 --> 00:14:15,620
And also just adding that look text made a huge difference when I started demoing it to people.

263
00:14:17,848 --> 00:14:20,569
And I think there's room to do things like seamless confusion detection,

264
00:14:20,589 --> 00:14:21,789
which is something that I've kind of worked on.

265
00:14:21,809 --> 00:14:23,649
I haven't gotten great results yet.

266
00:14:24,069 --> 00:14:26,090
But the idea is knowing all the stuff that's going on in a game,

267
00:14:26,130 --> 00:14:28,971
where the player's looking, whether they're looking around rapidly.

268
00:14:29,311 --> 00:14:31,852
You can figure out whether someone's confused and perhaps offer guidance.

269
00:14:32,392 --> 00:14:36,793
The problem is you can also incorporate verbal cues,

270
00:14:36,813 --> 00:14:38,773
like if people will often verbalize their confusion.

271
00:14:39,921 --> 00:14:41,762
The challenge of course is limiting false positives.

272
00:14:41,922 --> 00:14:43,643
Many people might, you know, there's lots of times

273
00:14:43,663 --> 00:14:45,164
when you might want to look away intentionally,

274
00:14:45,224 --> 00:14:46,265
like say you're talking to somebody

275
00:14:46,285 --> 00:14:47,745
and you don't want to start flashing indicators

276
00:14:47,765 --> 00:14:48,186
in front of the user.

277
00:14:51,391 --> 00:14:56,497
So far my ideas that I've kind of shown are not necessarily AR native, they're just adaptations of existing games.

278
00:14:57,118 --> 00:15:02,805
But one thing that came to mind is that you have a lot of information about where the player's head is at any given frame,

279
00:15:03,326 --> 00:15:05,208
so why not use that as an input device?

280
00:15:05,688 --> 00:15:09,433
So I came up with this little game concept that I think is closer to something that's really AR native.

281
00:15:10,374 --> 00:15:14,337
It makes use of the environment interactions and that kind of room scale experience.

282
00:15:15,058 --> 00:15:16,799
And it's something that really can only be done in AR.

283
00:15:17,160 --> 00:15:19,522
And people that have tried it have had a lot of fun.

284
00:15:19,602 --> 00:15:20,923
It's a very kinetic experience.

285
00:15:21,523 --> 00:15:24,506
And again, something that I think I'd like to revisit further if I had time.

286
00:15:27,709 --> 00:15:28,229
Ergonomics.

287
00:15:29,010 --> 00:15:30,631
An issue that came up in Doko desu ka?

288
00:15:30,951 --> 00:15:33,253
The experience, like many, takes place on the floor.

289
00:15:33,939 --> 00:15:36,421
and it's very uncomfortable to look at the floor for extended periods of time

290
00:15:36,922 --> 00:15:39,424
unless you happen to be Gaston from Beauty and the Beast.

291
00:15:39,504 --> 00:15:43,427
Most people don't have that kind of neck strength, so you want to think about that.

292
00:15:44,528 --> 00:15:46,570
In Doco Descartes, the solution was proposed by a co-worker.

293
00:15:46,590 --> 00:15:51,534
It's really simple. You just allow the map to be elevated and it works great.

294
00:15:52,835 --> 00:15:54,477
Simple solution, but definitely something to keep in mind.

295
00:15:54,657 --> 00:15:57,599
It's more comfortable to have your head looking up than it is down.

296
00:15:57,619 --> 00:15:57,679
Now,

297
00:16:01,663 --> 00:16:06,027
To really take advantage of augmented reality or mixed reality, I think you want to kind of get away from

298
00:16:07,688 --> 00:16:11,031
the design language of 2D screens. Unfortunately, I know I'm guilty of this myself.

299
00:16:11,171 --> 00:16:13,713
A lot of applications have 2D floating menus.

300
00:16:14,794 --> 00:16:18,217
But what's really a lot more effective than pasting something in front of someone's face

301
00:16:18,317 --> 00:16:21,380
is to just make it incorporate your UI elements as part of the environment.

302
00:16:21,560 --> 00:16:25,203
So for example, these buttons are 3D objects in the level itself.

303
00:16:26,724 --> 00:16:28,005
Also, what you can do is map.

304
00:16:29,873 --> 00:16:32,054
different kind of logical things that happen in the game

305
00:16:32,234 --> 00:16:34,215
to different spatial areas in the room.

306
00:16:34,756 --> 00:16:36,857
So in Doko Desu Ka, the original idea

307
00:16:36,877 --> 00:16:38,638
was to have an instructor that stands off to the side.

308
00:16:38,758 --> 00:16:39,758
I ended up with a blackboard,

309
00:16:39,819 --> 00:16:41,660
but the idea is that you look away from the game

310
00:16:41,680 --> 00:16:43,601
when you wanna learn or review vocabulary,

311
00:16:44,221 --> 00:16:45,682
and you kind of do that mental context switch.

312
00:16:45,742 --> 00:16:46,863
The game knows you're not looking at it,

313
00:16:46,883 --> 00:16:48,644
and then when you're ready, you go back to the game.

314
00:16:48,664 --> 00:16:50,765
And I think that's kind of a very natural feeling,

315
00:16:50,805 --> 00:16:54,427
very intuitive way to leverage space in UX design.

316
00:16:56,456 --> 00:16:58,717
So also a key differentiator between AR and VR, of course,

317
00:16:58,737 --> 00:17:01,079
that you can do this kind of like room scale stuff much more easily.

318
00:17:02,780 --> 00:17:04,901
So in summary, what have I learned about making things fun?

319
00:17:05,181 --> 00:17:08,143
I think what I've learned is that you want to keep a casual audience in mind.

320
00:17:08,423 --> 00:17:10,504
It'll be a while before these things become widely accessible.

321
00:17:10,984 --> 00:17:13,606
You'll have a lot of, you know, non-hardcore gamers using it,

322
00:17:14,026 --> 00:17:15,787
and you want to be attentive to their needs

323
00:17:16,627 --> 00:17:18,228
in kind of drawing them into these experiences.

324
00:17:19,780 --> 00:17:21,883
You can adapt many existing game mechanics,

325
00:17:22,384 --> 00:17:24,326
but I think the real payoff is in developing

326
00:17:24,666 --> 00:17:26,749
AR-native content, stuff that can only work

327
00:17:26,969 --> 00:17:27,750
on these platforms.

328
00:17:29,012 --> 00:17:31,054
A big part of that is making use of the environment.

329
00:17:31,155 --> 00:17:33,317
It adds that wow factor, and really,

330
00:17:33,357 --> 00:17:34,999
that's what makes things really AR-native.

331
00:17:35,019 --> 00:17:37,262
So there's a ton of opportunity to do creative things here.

332
00:17:38,822 --> 00:17:43,650
And just keep in mind that people enjoy creating and sharing things, and the ability to change

333
00:17:43,670 --> 00:17:45,854
their reality feels magical to them.

334
00:17:45,954 --> 00:17:49,080
And so you should really keep that in mind, I think, when designing games going forward

335
00:17:49,180 --> 00:17:49,841
for this kind of medium.

336
00:17:51,522 --> 00:17:55,144
I think there's a lot to look forward to in coming years, obviously improved headsets,

337
00:17:55,725 --> 00:17:56,905
and also the AR cloud.

338
00:17:57,205 --> 00:18:01,708
So for those who don't know, this idea of having a digital soft copy, so to speak, of

339
00:18:01,748 --> 00:18:06,430
the world, everything kind of mapped out and accessible to facilitate multi-user experiences,

340
00:18:06,450 --> 00:18:07,271
you know, persistence.

341
00:18:07,771 --> 00:18:11,593
And I think this will open up the door to what I would call like, you know, world-scale

342
00:18:12,013 --> 00:18:12,954
location-based gaming.

343
00:18:13,780 --> 00:18:17,502
And I wanted to leave you guys with this little prototype that I made, a little demo,

344
00:18:17,982 --> 00:18:23,684
using a major motion picture franchise for the art of what I think gaming might look like in 2021.

345
00:18:23,884 --> 00:18:33,848
Agent Nicole, do you read me?

346
00:18:35,229 --> 00:18:40,551
Copy that. I've got your video and sensors.

347
00:18:40,571 --> 00:18:41,351
So this is the place?

348
00:18:41,391 --> 00:18:41,491
Yes.

349
00:18:43,813 --> 00:18:44,694
Doesn't look like much.

350
00:18:44,714 --> 00:18:46,974
I'll bet that's just the way they want it.

351
00:18:47,014 --> 00:18:48,634
All right, I'm going in.

352
00:18:48,754 --> 00:18:53,635
I'm picking up signs of motion. Be careful.

353
00:18:53,695 --> 00:18:56,096
This doesn't look good.

354
00:19:15,802 --> 00:19:20,408
Get out of there.

355
00:19:22,591 --> 00:19:25,776
Head for the exit.

356
00:19:39,598 --> 00:19:43,520
So is it actually arriving in 2021? Well, I think that depends on people in this room.

357
00:19:43,680 --> 00:19:46,861
I hope that it becomes a reality and if you guys don't make it, I think maybe I will.

358
00:19:48,622 --> 00:19:52,083
So that's pretty much it. I think we have 10 minutes now for questions.

359
00:19:52,743 --> 00:19:56,285
If anybody would like to ask any questions, feel free. Thank you.

360
00:20:11,942 --> 00:20:13,683
Nicole Lizaro from Z Design.

361
00:20:13,903 --> 00:20:18,247
I was curious, what do you think is the largest unsolved problem?

362
00:20:18,667 --> 00:20:24,531
What would you like us to do next for creating good experiences for AR games?

363
00:20:25,032 --> 00:20:26,713
What is the largest unsolved problem?

364
00:20:26,753 --> 00:20:27,814
I think that's a very good question.

365
00:20:28,715 --> 00:20:34,019
I think, gosh, there's a lot of stuff, but I think that if I had to pick one thing

366
00:20:34,299 --> 00:20:38,102
that I certainly want to investigate going forward is the object recognition segmentation

367
00:20:38,122 --> 00:20:40,523
and making that much more easy to deal with.

368
00:20:41,273 --> 00:20:43,295
I think that would really facilitate a lot.

369
00:20:44,236 --> 00:20:47,519
That and of course, just improvements in sensing

370
00:20:47,539 --> 00:20:48,940
and so forth, but I think object recognition,

371
00:20:48,980 --> 00:20:50,101
if I had to list one thing,

372
00:20:50,581 --> 00:20:51,983
that I think could make things really magical.

373
00:20:52,303 --> 00:20:53,844
So you know that it would be AI,

374
00:20:53,864 --> 00:20:56,386
a difference between a coffee table and a couch,

375
00:20:56,467 --> 00:20:58,248
because your character would do different things

376
00:20:58,308 --> 00:20:58,969
if it was on each side.

377
00:20:58,989 --> 00:21:00,590
Exactly, yeah, being able to detect that quickly

378
00:21:00,610 --> 00:21:03,993
and having a way of robustly categorizing

379
00:21:04,033 --> 00:21:05,094
what the play space looks like,

380
00:21:05,234 --> 00:21:07,696
I think would be just super amazing.

381
00:21:08,243 --> 00:21:12,007
I want to play a game where it knows that the best place to hide the body is in my fridge.

382
00:21:12,328 --> 00:21:13,710
Exactly, right, right, right.

383
00:21:14,651 --> 00:21:14,951
Thank you.

384
00:21:14,971 --> 00:21:17,414
Thank you.

385
00:21:17,534 --> 00:21:23,642
For developers, what other tools are available for geolocated-based gaming other than the

386
00:21:23,682 --> 00:21:26,205
new Google Maps feature and Mapbox?

387
00:21:27,669 --> 00:21:30,311
In terms of geolocation, I'm actually not sure, unfortunately.

388
00:21:30,671 --> 00:21:31,231
I wish I knew.

389
00:21:31,831 --> 00:21:33,892
I know that Google recently released that API.

390
00:21:35,173 --> 00:21:36,554
On the HoloLens right now, for example,

391
00:21:36,974 --> 00:21:39,375
there's no real built-in geolocation capability.

392
00:21:39,395 --> 00:21:40,175
There's no GPS.

393
00:21:40,756 --> 00:21:42,176
You'd have to do it through Wi-Fi or something.

394
00:21:43,277 --> 00:21:44,317
I really don't know, and that's, I think,

395
00:21:44,597 --> 00:21:47,379
an area that's being, I think there are lots of

396
00:21:47,979 --> 00:21:49,180
small startups working on things,

397
00:21:49,240 --> 00:21:51,901
but unfortunately I don't have any understanding of that.

398
00:21:55,036 --> 00:21:57,461
When you were scanning the room for the game,

399
00:21:57,522 --> 00:22:00,649
what's the time frame for the calibration of the room

400
00:22:00,689 --> 00:22:02,392
between scanning it and starting the game?

401
00:22:03,001 --> 00:22:03,781
That's a really good question.

402
00:22:03,801 --> 00:22:05,222
The question was, you know, how long does it take

403
00:22:05,262 --> 00:22:07,223
from scanning the room to starting a game?

404
00:22:07,564 --> 00:22:09,745
And the room scan itself can take quite a while.

405
00:22:09,965 --> 00:22:12,306
I use the Spatial Understanding Library,

406
00:22:12,366 --> 00:22:15,948
which post-processes the raw spatial mesh even further.

407
00:22:16,368 --> 00:22:17,989
So it can take a bit of time,

408
00:22:18,009 --> 00:22:20,251
depending on the play space to scan the space.

409
00:22:20,731 --> 00:22:21,651
So you're looking at like,

410
00:22:21,752 --> 00:22:23,032
you could spend like 30 seconds

411
00:22:23,072 --> 00:22:24,453
to a minute to two minutes scanning,

412
00:22:24,853 --> 00:22:26,854
if you want like a, you know, the full area scanned.

413
00:22:27,555 --> 00:22:28,475
And then on top of that,

414
00:22:28,495 --> 00:22:31,077
depending on how you implement your placement solver

415
00:22:31,137 --> 00:22:31,497
after that.

416
00:22:32,340 --> 00:22:35,322
It can take anywhere from like 10 seconds in my room

417
00:22:35,382 --> 00:22:37,384
to place the objects to I've seen some places

418
00:22:37,404 --> 00:22:39,185
where it gets confused and it spends like almost a minute.

419
00:22:39,485 --> 00:22:42,448
Now that's partly because I didn't use

420
00:22:42,468 --> 00:22:43,929
the most efficient way of placing things

421
00:22:43,969 --> 00:22:45,350
and invoking the constraint solver.

422
00:22:45,790 --> 00:22:47,071
That I think could be easily improved.

423
00:22:47,491 --> 00:22:49,453
But you're definitely looking at sucking up

424
00:22:49,493 --> 00:22:50,394
about a minute of time.

425
00:22:50,474 --> 00:22:53,656
And so in my game, once you've scanned a space,

426
00:22:54,036 --> 00:22:54,977
I make sure to retain that.

427
00:22:54,997 --> 00:22:56,098
So if you start a level over again,

428
00:22:56,118 --> 00:22:57,839
it asks you do you wanna just reuse the previous scan

429
00:22:57,859 --> 00:22:59,240
so you don't have to keep going through and doing it.

430
00:22:59,841 --> 00:23:00,461
It is slow though.

431
00:23:01,415 --> 00:23:04,235
How long before it's not exact real time,

432
00:23:04,255 --> 00:23:05,936
but near real time where you could like walk

433
00:23:05,996 --> 00:23:09,997
into the bedroom and delay you for a couple seconds

434
00:23:10,037 --> 00:23:11,177
or something and then kind of pop up there?

435
00:23:11,257 --> 00:23:12,037
That's a great question.

436
00:23:12,237 --> 00:23:15,358
I think it's really just a year or two away.

437
00:23:15,458 --> 00:23:18,219
So the AR cloud stuff that I mentioned,

438
00:23:18,259 --> 00:23:19,039
that's kind of that idea.

439
00:23:19,079 --> 00:23:21,159
The idea is that they'll be able to kind of crowdsource

440
00:23:21,619 --> 00:23:23,340
scans and so when you walk into a place

441
00:23:23,360 --> 00:23:24,240
that's already been scanned,

442
00:23:24,660 --> 00:23:26,640
it recognizes that and loads the room data.

443
00:23:27,761 --> 00:23:29,361
I'm not on one of these teams that develops the hardware,

444
00:23:29,421 --> 00:23:30,981
but from what I've kind of heard leaked to me.

445
00:23:31,802 --> 00:23:35,684
It sounds to me like this problem will be alleviated a lot within the next year.

446
00:23:36,044 --> 00:23:39,065
So I think we're not very far off.

447
00:23:39,085 --> 00:23:42,247
So certainly within two years when this stuff is more mainstream, I think you'll see the

448
00:23:42,267 --> 00:23:44,047
scanning phase be done much more rapidly.

449
00:23:44,187 --> 00:23:44,368
Cool.

450
00:23:44,788 --> 00:23:45,188
Great talk.

451
00:23:45,228 --> 00:23:45,728
Thanks for sharing.

452
00:23:45,868 --> 00:23:46,168
Thank you.

